      passage: `<p>To historians, the Piast dynasty’s long rule stands out as vital to the very making of the Polish state. Some, though, tell apart a well-attested duke such as Władysław I Herman, on the throne from 1079 to 1102 CE, from dimmer names such as Lestek, put by tradition in the ninth and tenth centuries but of quite uncertain reality. Lestek does turn up in the <em>Gesta principum Polonorum</em>—a chronicle of medieval Poland written between 1112 and 1118—yet there his entry rests on oral tradition, as the records of the later rulers do not.</p>`,
      prompt: `According to the text, what is a difference between how historians view Lestek and how they view Władysław I Herman?`,
